comments.text:
Well, IQ is a composite measure of a bunch of things, but although IQ is a 
gauge of intelligence, it's not an absolute scale. What it really aims to 
describe is a person's intelligence, or more generally their mental 
development, in relation to his/her peers. For example, a 5 year old with 
an IQ of 100 is right on par which is why values near 100 are most common. 
A 5 year old with an IQ of 150, however, is considered as mentally 
developed as a 7.5 year old. Conversely, a 5 year old with an IQ of 50 has 
the mental development of a 2.5 year old. So a 5 year old with an IQ of 150 
is not smarter than an adult with an average IQ. IQ tests take into account 
not only math, science, language and critical thinking skills, but also 
things such as cultural awareness, understanding of relationships, 
maturity, self control, and morality. This is why you should never trust 
online free IQ tests that only present puzzles like anagrams or overly 
wordy math problems, because they aren't testing the complete spectrum of 
mental development that IQ tests seek to describe. So in relation to your 
question, yes, learning new things such as this does increase your IQ, 
albeit very little, but it does. And before you ask, yes, it is possible to 
manually increase your IQ through education, but don't expect to get even a 
single IQ point out of watching vsauce's videos: it takes a large amount of 
work to get even one IQ point.

People from the States can love their Constitution and "freedom", but I'm 
thankful that here in Hungary you CAN'T name your children anything. Saving 
a lot of kids from a lifetime of hell as "Bulldozer", "Twiggy Branch", 
"Texan Princess" or "Power Driller Mk3". US naming freedom just sucks.
Mind you, you can name your baby a proper name without approval with any of 
the (gender fitting) names already established in a list of previously 
approved names, or in case of a foreign parent, his/her country. Otherwise 
name proposals are screened and they would be only approved by the relevant 
council if said name is used in another language, if it wouldn't cause harm 
to the child later (bullying, puns etc.), and if it fits the phonology of 
Hungarian. Oh and unisex names aren't allowed this way either.

So for example Kevin or Léa would probably be accepted upon request, since 
they aren't shameful and are pronounceable by any Hungarian without prior 
exposure to them.﻿

comments.text:
Interesting, I guess the States shouldn't have any rule about naming 
because it's a cultural mashup where citizenship, race, ethnicity are all 
getting blurred (like US citizens with Irish ancestry). But yes, in a lot 
of more homogenous countries naming laws aren't seen as that bad, and so 
far, there weren't any upheaval, probably because even Chinese here name 
there children here with Hungarian names (or they get a foreign name 
accepted, I don't know the exact law regarding second-generation children).

As I see, people who are proponents of naming laws (including me) think 
that stupid names are somewhat of a shame to the nation of the beholder. As 
I'm living in a country with (pretty lax, imho) naming laws good for our 
99.9% majority, I'm fine, but I get horrified by some names in the US when 
they pop up on the Internet.

Interesting fact that we have a racial minority (I wont say which) who 
often decide they want American (Jessica) or Italian (Armando) sounding 
names.

Also Mercedes, or rather, Mercédesz is a perfectly okay name here, though 
it might be perceived as a little bit fancy if used with a plain family 
name, eg. Smith. I happen to know two Mercedes, and neither of them belong 
to wealthy families. Not among the most common names here, but relatively 
common. I can imagine it though that people in the States think more of the 
car brand, but Mercedeses and other foreign cars are so common here that we 
don't really think of the car when hearing the name. Though it was a name 
first, car brand second, because of the founder's daughter. So it doesn't 
really connect with wealth, for whatever reason.

(To show you some of the less common, but perfectly applicable female 
names, we have Lea, Kornélia, Xénia, Roxána, Liliána, Petra, Olga, Kitti, 
Franciska and Lujza. I really think we have plenty of nice names to choose 
from even with the naming law.)
comments.author: Rev Snowfox

comments.text:
Well, you also have to acknowledge that the case being made for a more 
homogeneous country like Hungary isn't really applicable in a place as 
culturally diverse as the US or the UK. If you guys had as big of an 
immigrant influx of, say, Arabs as the UK or France has had, there'd be 
some pretty significant outcry from that community to change the law so 
they can give their children born in Hungary Arab names.

Also, bizarre names are waaaaay less prevalent in the US than you'd think. 
Yeah, you scratch your head when it happens, but usually people with odd 
names here in the US usually fall under 1 of 2 categories:

1. Children of wealthy parents (named Mercedes, etc.) who are well off 
enough that their name doesn't really impact their well being.

2. Children of... more insular communities based on racial background (not 
gonna say which) who are among others with similarly unconventional names.

comments.text:
As far as I know the legal situation with building codes here, every city 
district has a local code which might or might not disallow buildings that 
are "disrupting the surrounding view" (ie. too gaudy, flashy, silly looking 
etc. compared to the other houses on the streets) for aesthetic reasons.

In my view, requiring Hungarian kids to be named in Hungarian names is 
similar to this, to enforce some kind of familiar commonality among us, 
filtering out the wacky and weird stuff parents might come up with on a 
whim (as you know the children can't be asked about their choice). On a 
side note, the US has a lots of ethnicities and immigrants, but we don't 
really, so it's natural that 99,9% of people here doesn't even want foreign 
or previously non-existent names for their babies, but happily choose from 
the already used few hundred names without lamenting about the fact they 
technically don't have a free choice. Those who want to give something 
different are most likely allowed to do so because of their citizenship. Or 
they just wait for the approval if it sounds sane and if it's pronounciable 
by the first look. (I saw some silly ones already allowed, so it's not like 
you can't name your baby girl a pretty sounding foreign name if you want 
to...)

I presume we cannot compare the naming practices of certain countries, 
especially not if one of them is the US. We probably need that 
"nationalism" or "patriotism" or whatever you might call it, which is 
implied by using Hungarian names for Hungarian kids. (That's a long story, 
but we as a nation imho really need more self-confidence after the 
communist rule. Which would be funny with folks with French or Dutch or 
American names running around.)

I see your point of the totalitarian aspect, but it's not unusual, if you 
look at Japan, even naturalized foreigners have to adopt a Japanese name 
(written with those moon runes) as a legal name. Naturally, all Japanese 
are given Japanese names, and afaik this is the law there. And they neither 
let embarrassing names or names with bad implications pass.

captions.text: Hey, Vsauce. My name

is Michael.
And my name is Kevin.
Names.
Humans give each other names
but so do dolphins. They use
whistle sounds and will respond to their whistle name
even when produced by a dolphin they don't know.
Personal names, personalized
things, signifying that the named thing is capable of

feeling. That it's worthy of empathy.
The United Nations

Convention on the Rights of the Child
has declared that every
human child born on earth has the right

to a name.
Every country on earth has ratified the treaty,

except for three: South Sudan,
the newest country on earth,
Somalia, which has no central government, and
the United States. Why?
Well, some organizations
inside the United States believe that the US

shouldn't have to listen to another
authority and the treaty prohibits
the death penalty for children.
It's a moot point now but up until 2005 twenty-two states
allowed children to be executed

for crimes. The United States follows the
treaty now but won't promise to
always do so. Dunce is

a bad name to be called
but an even worse name
to be the origin of. Meet Duns
Scotus, born in 1266.

Popular in his time, later scholars looked
down on his teachings as

clever but wrong.
They were so critical, in fact, they took
Duns and turned his name into a noun meaning
a stupid person - a dunce.
Perhaps you'd rather have had the longest name

ever. A record held by a man born in 1904
whose name was 746 letters

long.
You can listen to someone pronounce the entire name
on Wikipedia. What can't
a name be? Mononymous people only use
one name. You can name your kid Apple or
North or Moon Unit. You can name your kid

Football. But not everywhere.
Some countries require parents to submit
their children's names to the government

for approval.
New Zealand enforces a policy in which names
must not cause offence to a reasonable person,

not be unreasonably long and should not
resemble an official title

or rank.
For example, their courts recently forbid a mother
from naming her child "Sex Fruit."
But New Zealand has allowed some unusual names.
Right now, in New Zealand, there are children living

whose names are officially "Violence,"
"Midnight Chardonnay"
and "Number 16 Bus Shelter."
In 1996 a Swedish couple submitted their child's name

for official approval, "Albin."
But in protest of the naming laws in place at
the time,
they spelled Albin like this
It wasn't accepted.

In the United States you can name your
kid pretty much anything that doesn't
include obscenity,

numerals or symbols, which means,
as Carlton Larson points out,
you can't name your kid R2-D2.
But you could, say, name your child
Adolf Hitler, which Heath and Deborah Campbell
did in 2006. Adolf Hitler Campbell

made headlines in 2009 after a bakery
refused to put his name
on a cake for his third birthday. Shortly afterwards

child welfare officials took him and his
other controversially named siblings away
from their parents and place them in foster care,

where they remain to this day.
His parents are self-identified
Nazis and they live in

New Jersey, the latter of which
makes them New Jerseyans.

If they lived in Kansas they'd be Kansan,
if they lived in New York they'd

be New Yorkers,
if they lived in Utah they'd be
Utahns. A name based on where something is from
is called a demonym, which means that even names

have names.
An endonym is a name given to a place

by those who live there.
An exonym is the name given to a place by those

who live elsewhere.
But my favorite name for a name

is an autoantonym.
A word that can mean the

opposite of its other meaning.
For example,
the word "off," which can mean both
activated and de-activated.
For instance, the alarm went off,
so we had to turn it off.

You can track the distribution of your
last name across the entire
earth using the public profiler.
Or visualize the popularity of the US' top

1000 names over time.
Studies have shown that your name
may influence your behavior.

The name–letter effect is a phenomenon
in which people prefer
words, events, other people and places,

which contain letters similar to the
letters inside their own

name.
Measuring a person's preference for such letters
has been shown to be a good gauge of self-esteem.

Richard Wiseman's Quirkology is a great
read on this topic. He mentions

"alphabetical discrimination."
People with last names that begin with the letter
near the end of the alphabet tend to rate themselves

significantly less successful than
people with names that begin with the
letter near the
beginning of the alphabet. Perhaps because
all their lives they've been put on the bottom

of lists.
Also fascinating is the fact that men and women with
positive initials, like "A.C.E.,"
"H.U.G." or "J.O.Y."
live 3 to 4.5 years longer

than average.
But men with negative initials, like
"P.I.G.," "B.U.M." or "D.I.E."
die about three years

earlier than average.
But interestingly, women with negative initials

don't show much difference.
Half of all
Americans share the same 1,712

last names.
1 percent of Americans have the last name

Smith.
In China, 85%

share the same 100 last names.
Two-hundred last names cover 96% of the population
in Vietnam, 40% of which have the same
last name.
This one.

Name Colleen can hurt people's feelings.
It's at the very bottom

of Graham's hierarchy of disagreement.
And, at the end of the day,
names are just words. As the saying goes,

sticks and stones may break my bones but
words are merely the smallest element of
language capable of

containing meaning and isolation and, 
as such, could never directly produce the 4,000
newtons
of force per square centimetre required to break bones.

thanks for watching.
